<HTML>  
<HEAD>  
<TITLE>Court TV Library: Newsmakers -- Annie Leibovitz Files Suit 
Against Paramount Pictures</TITLE>  
</HEAD>  
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000"   
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">  
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG  
SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP   
ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>  
<BR CLEAR=ALL>  
<P>Paramount Pictures superimposed comic actor Leslie Neilsen's face 
over a portrait of a pregnant Demi Moore to promote the film, "Naked 
Gun 33 1/3." Photographer Annie Leibovitz filed suit Dec. 18, 1996 
against Paramount over its use of the copyrighted photo, which she shot 
for the cover of Vanity Fair magazine. </P> 


<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>  
<PRE>  
 
 
 
UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT 
SOUTHERN DISTRICT OF NEW YORK 
 
 
ANNIE LEIBOVITZ, 
 
Plaintiff, 
 
- against - 
 
 
PARAMOUNT PICTURES CORPORATION, 
 
Defendant. 
 
 
Civil Action No. 

COMPLAINT 

PLAINTIFF DEMANDS A JURY TRIAL 


Plaintiff Annie Leibovitz, by her attorneys, Norwick & Schad, for her 
complaint, alleges as follows:  


INTRODUCTORY STATEMENT 
 
1. Plaintiff Annie Leibovitz ("plaintiff") is a professional photographer of 
international reputation. Her distinctive and widely acclaimed photographs 
have been published editorially and in advertising in all media throughout 
the world. Her photographs appear in the editorial pages of Vanity Fair 
magazine on a regular basis.  
 
 
JURISDICTION AND VENUE 
 
2. This is an action for copyright infringement arising under the Copyright 
Act of 1976, 17 U.S.C. Sec. 101 et seq. Jurisdiction over this action is 
conferred by 28 U.S.C. Secs. 1331 and 1338.  
 
3. Venue is proper within the Southern District of New York, under 28 
U.S.C. Sec. 1400.  
 
 
THE PARTIES 
 
4. Plaintiff is an American citizen by birth, residing in the County and City 
of New York.  
 
5. Upon information and belief, defendant Paramount Pictures Corporation 
("defendant") is a California corporation having its principal place of 
business in Los Angeles, California, with offices in the City, County and 
State of New York.  
 
 
STATEMENT OF FACTS 
 
6. In early 1991, plaintiff photographed the actress Demi Moore on 
assignment for Vanity Fair magazine, a publication of Advance Magazine 
Publishers Inc. d/b/a The Conde Nast Publications Inc. ("Conde Nast"). 
One of plaintiff's photographs of Demi Moore (the "Photograph"), 
attached as Exhibit A hereto, was published with permission on the cover 
of the August 1991 issue of Vanity Fair.  
 
7. The August 1991 issue of Vanity Fair was duly registered for copyright 
by Conde Nast on July 31, 1991 under Registration No. 3 109 469. 
Plaintiff, as the photographer, is the beneficial and sole owner of all right, 
title and interest in the copyright in the Photograph.  
 
8. In late 1993 or early 1994, defendant commenced an international 
advertising campaign for its motion picture, "Naked Gun 33 1/3, the Final 
Insult" (the "Film"), about to be released in March 1994. The 
advertisements featured the Photograph, or a copy of it, attached as 
Exhibit B, superimposing over the face of Demi Moore the face of Leslie 
Neilsen, the star of the Film.  
 
9. Starting in early 1994, defendant caused advertisements featuring the 
Copy to be published in print media in this district, in the United States 
and, upon information and belief, throughout the world. Moreover, on 
information and belief, the Copy also appeared on posters advertising the 
Film in motion picture theaters throughout the world. The advertisements 
and posters featuring the Copy bore the legend, "Copyright 1993 by 
Paramount Pictures, All Rights Reserved."  
 
10. Plaintiff and her agent, Contact Press Images, Inc., through their 
attorneys, wrote to defendant on March 14, 1994 that the pervasive and 
unauthorized use of the Photograph was a calculated and willful violation 
of the copyright in the Photograph and that its continued use by defendant 
would only compound the injury.  
 
11. By letter of March 17, 1994, defendant informed plaintiff's counsel 
that defendant did not reproduce the Photograph in the advertisements. 
Rather, defendant wrote that the photograph (the Copy) which appeared in 
the advertisements "was a specially commissioned photograph of a model 
hired for the ad campaign." By letter of March 25, 1994, counsel for 
plaintiff notified defendant that the intentional copying of the Photograph 
only aggravated the infringement.  
 
12. Defendant did not respond to the letter. Instead it continued its willful 
and intentional infringement of plaintiff's registered copyright, in total 
disregard of plaintiff's rights.  
 
 
CLAIM FOR RELIEF 
 
13. Plaintiff repeats and realleges each and every allegation set forth in 
Paragraphs 1 through 13 herein.  
 
14. By its actions alleged above, defendant has infringed and continues to 
infringe plaintiff's copyright in the Photograph. -  
 
WHEREFORE, plaintiff respectfully requests judgment against defendant 
as follows:  
 
(1) that defendant, its officers, directors, principals, agents, servants, 
employees, successors and assigns, and all those in active concert or 
participation with it, be preliminarily and permanently enjoined and 
restrained from infringing the copyright in the Photograph in any manner;  
 
(2) that defendant's infringements be found to have been intentional and 
willful;  
 
(3) that defendant be required to pay to plaintiff statutory damages 
pursuant to the Copyright Act, 17 U.S.C. Secs. 101 et seq.;  
 
(4) that defendant be required to account for all gains and profits 
attributable to defendant's acts of infringement;  
 
(5) that defendant be required to pay to plaintiff actual damages according 
to proof and all profits attributable to the infringements of plaintiff's 
copyright;  
 
(6) that plaintiff be awarded plaintiff's costs and attorneys' fees, pursuant 
to 17 U.S.C. Secs. 101 et seq. and  
 
(7) that the Court grant such other relief as the Court deems proper.  
 
Dated: December 19, 1994 
New York, New York 
 
NORWICK & SCHAD 
 
/s/ 
Tennyson Schad (TS 8066) 
Attorneys for Plaintiff 
One Madison Avenue 
New York, New York 10010 
Tel: (212)-447-5000 
</PRE> 
