<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Library: Government -- FBI Agent Charged with Hiding Ruby Ridge 
Papers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000" 
BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<A HREF="/map/library.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/library.gif" ISMAP 
ALT="Court TV Library" BORDER="0"></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>FBI official, E. Michael Kahoe has been charged with obstruction of justice in 
connection with the criminal investigation of white separatists Randy Weaver and Kevin 
Harris. Weaver and Harris were charged and later acquitted of first-degree murder in the 
death of Deputy U.S. Marshal William Degan, who was shot and killed on August 21, 
1992, in a confrontation near Ruby Ridge, Idaho. Kahoe, former chief of the FBI's 
violent crime section, was ordered to prepare a critique of the Ruby Ridge incident. 
Prosecutors in this case allege that Kahoe withheld the critique from the Weaver 
prosecution team, destroyed his copies of the critique, and ordered a subordinate official 
to destroy all copies of the critique and to make it appear as if the critique never 
existed.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>

U.S. Department of Justice

United States Attorney

District of Columbia

Contact: Kevin A. Ohlson
(202) 514-6933

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE
October 22, 1996


PRESS RELEASE

Michael R. Stiles
Acting United States Attorney
for the District of Columbia

U.S. Attorney Michael R. Stiles announced that obstruction of justice charges were filed 
today in the Ruby Ridge matter against E. Michael Kahoe, former Special Agent in 
Charge of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's Jacksonville, Florida, office. 

U.S. Attorney Stiles stated, "The Information alleges that Kahoe participated in the 
concealment and destruction of an FBI Headquarters document that was bought by 
prosecutors in preparation for the murder trial pertaining to the Ruby Ridge incident in 
Idaho." 

The Information charges Kahoe with Obstruction of Justice in connection with the federal 
criminal trial in 1993 of Randall C. Weaver and Kevin L. Harris. Weaver and Harris were 
charged with the first degree murder of Deputy U.S. Marshal William Degan, who was 
shot and killed on August 21, 1992, in a confrontation with Randall Weaver, his son 
Samuel, and Harris near Ruby Ridge, Idaho. Samuel Weaver was also killed in the 
firefight. 

The Information alleges that Kahoe was the Chief of the Violent Crimes and Major 
Offenders Section at the Headquarters of the Federal Bureau of Investigation ("FBI") in 
Washington, D.C. during the relevant time period. Upon learning of the August 21, 1992, 
events at Ruby Ridge, officials at FBI Headquarters ordered the FBI's Hostage Rescue 
Team ("HRT") deployed to Idaho. On August 22, 1992, an HRT sniper fired two shots 
from a position overlooking the Weaver cabin. The first round struck and wounded 
Randall Weaver. The second struck and killed Weaver's wife, Vicki, and also wounded 
Harris. The ensuing stand-off between federal law enforcement and the surviving 
members of the Weaver family and Harris concluded when Harris surrendered on August 
30, 1992, and Weaver and his three daughters surrendered on August 31, 1992, 

The Information further alleges that after the stand-off at Ruby Ridge, Kahoe was ordered 
by superiors to prepare an "after action critique" of the FBI's conduct at Ruby Ridge. 
Kahoe accordingly organized and moderated an after action conference on the Ruby 
Ridge matter at FBI Headquarters in November of 1992. He then ordered that a written 
Ruby Ridge after action critique be prepared, and participated in the editing of that 
document. In early January of 1993, Kahoe received the Ruby Ridge after action critique, 
along with copies sufficient for distribution to the after action conference participants and 
his superiors. 

Meanwhile, a federal grand jury in Idaho returned an indictment charging Weaver and 
Harris with the first degree murder of Deputy U.S. Marshal Degan. Prosecution of that 
case was assigned to the United States Attorney's Office in Idaho. 

The Information alleges that the Idaho U.S. Attorney's Office requested FBI 
Headquarters' documentation related to the Ruby Ridge matter. The Idaho U.S. Attorney's 
Office informed the FBI that such material was needed in order to prepare its case 
effectively and to determine whether there were materials to which the defense was 
entitled under constitutional requirements, rules of criminal discovery, or local court 
practice. On January 6, 1993, the Idaho U.S. Attorney's Office wrote a letter to the FBI 
reiterating its need for FBI Headquarters documentation and specifically requesting any 
FBI "documents or reports of any evaluations or critiques" of the actions of the FBI HRT 
at Ruby Ridge. Kahoe allegedly received a copy of this letter soon after it was sent. 

The Information alleges that Kahoe and certain of his superiors at FBI Headquarters 
resisted the Idaho U.S. Attorney's Office request for Headquarters documents. As a result, 
officials at the Department of Justice in Washington were asked to intervene. The 
Department of Justice eventually ordered, and the FBI eventually agreed, that all of the 
Ruby Ridge related Headquarters documents, including any disputed documents, should 
be produced to the prosecution team in Idaho. 

The Information alleges that Kahoe supervised the production of these documents to the 
prosecution team. In order to ensure that the Ruby Ridge after action critique would not 
be available in the Weaver case, however, Kahoe allegedly withheld the critique from the 
documents to be delivered to the prosecution team, destroyed all of his copies of the 
critique, and ordered a subordinate FBI Headquarters official to destroy all copies of the 
critique and to make it appear as if the critique never existed. 

Under federal law, a violation of the obstruction of justice statute carries a maximum 
penalty of ten years in prison and a $250,000 fine. 

The charge contained in the Information is merely an allegation. Mr. Kahoe is presumed 
innocent until and unless he is proven guilty. 

U.S. Attorney Stiles commended the investigative work of a Joint Task. Force consisting 
of U.S. Postal Inspectors and FBI Agent". He also commended the work of Assistant U.S. 
Attorneys Eric W. Sitarchuk, Robert E. Goldman, Steven W. Pelak and Carol Fortine. 



UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT
FOR THE DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA


UNITED STATES OF AMERICA

v.

H. MICHAEL KAHOE

Defendant.


CRIMINAL No.:
ORIGINAL:
VIOLATION:
18 U.S.C. Sec. 1512(b)(2)(B)
(Obstruction of Justice)


INFORMATION

The United States, informs the Court and charges that: 

1. At all times material to this Information, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE was the 
Chief of the Violent crimes and Major Offenders section at the Headquarters of the 
Federal Bureau of Investigation ("FBI") in Washington, D. C. 


The Incident at Ruby Ridge

2. On or about August 21, 1992, near an area known as Ruby Ridge, Idaho, deputies of 
the United States Marshals Service came in contact with Randall C. Weaver, his son 
Samuel and a Weaver family friend, Kevin L. Harris. A fire-fight ensued. Deputy U.S. 
Marshal William F. Degan and Samuel Weaver were shot and killed. 

3. Upon receiving notification of the events near Ruby Ridge, officials at the headquarters 
of the FBI ordered the Hostage Rescue Team ("HRT") of the FBI deployed to Idaho. The 
FBI also activated its headquarters' strategic command center from which FBI 
headquarters officials participated in the management and coordination of FBI operations 
at Ruby Ridge. 

4. On or about August 22, 1992, FBI HRT sniper teams took positions overlooking the 
Weaver cabin. An HRT sniper then fired two shots. The first round struck And wounded 
Randall Weaver. The second struck both Weaver's wife, Vicki, and Harris. Vicki Weaver 
was killed almost instantly. Harris was wounded. 

5. A stand-off between federal law enforcement and the surviving member" of the 
Weaver family and Harris followed. It concluded when Harris surrendered on or about 
August 30, 1992, and Randall Weaver and his daughters surrendered on or about August 
31, 1992. 

6. On or about November 19, 1992, a federal grand jury in Idaho returned a second 
superseding indictment charging Weaver and Harris with, among other offenses, the first 
degree murder of Deputy U.S. Marshal Degan. The case was captioned United States v. 
Randall C. Weaver and Kevin L. Harris, D. Idaho Crim. No. 92-090-N-EJL (hereinafter 
"the Weaver Case"). The trial of that matter commenced on April 13, 1993 and a verdict 
was returned on July 8, 1993. 


The FBI's Ruby Ridge After Action Critique 

7. Following a major crisis, it was a practice of FBI Headquarters to analyze and critique 
the FBI's performance during the crisis. This typically included an after action 
conference, which was attended by FBI supervisory participants in the crisis, followed by 
the preparation of a written "after action critique." The written critique typically detailed 
the facts of the crisis, as described by participants in the crisis who attended the 
conference, and then summarized findings and recommendations made during the 
conference. 

8. After the stand-off at Ruby Ridge, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE was ordered by 
superiors, whose identities are known to the United States, to prepare an "after action 
critique" of the FBI's conduct at Ruby Ridge. As a result of this direction, defendant E. 
MICHAEL KAHOE organized and moderated an after action conference on the Ruby 
Ridge matter at FBI Headquarters on November 2, 1992. Conference attendees included 
FBI officials who participated in the crisis either at Ruby Ridge or FBI Headquarters. 

9. Thereafter, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE ordered that a written Ruby Ridge after 
action critique be prepared (hereinafter "the Ruby Ridge after action critique"), and 
participated in the editing of that document. 

10. In or about the first week of January, 1993, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE 
received the Ruby Ridge after action critique, along with copies sufficient for distribution 
to the after action conference participants and his superiors at FBI Headquarters. 


Destruction of the After Action Critique 

11. Prosecution of the Weaver case was assigned to the United States Attorney's Office in 
Idaho. Aware of the involvement of FBI Headquarters in the crisis, the Idaho U.S. 
Attorney's Office, with the assistance of local FBI agents assigned to the case, requested 
FBI Headquarters' documentation related to the Ruby Ridge matter. The Idaho U.S. 
Attorney's Office informed the FBI that such documentation was needed in order to 
prepare its case effectively and to determine whether there were materials to which the 
defense was entitled under constitutional requirements, rules of criminal discovery or 
local court practice. 

12. On or about January 6, 1993, the Idaho U.S. Attorney's Office wrote a letter to the 
FBI reiterating it" need for FBI Headquarters documentation. The letter also specifically 
requested any FBI "documents or reports of any evaluations or critiques" of the actions of 
the FBI HRT at Ruby Ridge. Defendant B. MICHAEL KAHOE received a copy of this 
letter soon after it was sent. 

13. The defendant, in conjunction with certain of his superiors at FBI Headquarters, 
whose identities are known to the United States, resulted the Idaho U.S. Attorney's Office 
request for Headquarters documents. As a result, officials at the Department of Justice in 
Washington were asked to intervene. 

14. Thereafter, beginning on or about January 7, 1993, and continuing through early 
April, 1993, a series of meetings and conversations on the issue of FBI Headquarters 
document production occurred between Department of Justice officials and FBI officials, 
including defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE. 

15. At a meeting on or about January 7, 1993, it was agreed between the Department of 
Justice, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE and another mentor FBI official, whose 
identity $6 known to the United States, that the Idaho prosecutors would first be allowed 
to see, but not copy or retain, specific documents whose production the FBI continued to 
oppose. 

16. This procedure was designed to permit the Idaho prosecution team the opportunity to 
make specific arguments as to why they believed that either they or the defense were 
entitled to have the disputed documents. It was also designed to allow the Department of 
Justice to consider the arguments of both the prosecutors and FBI Headquarters with 
respect to whether those documents should be produced. 

17. Between on or about January 7 and January 12, 1993, defendant E. MICHAEL 
KAHOE supervised the compilation of the documents whose production the FBI 
disputed. In order to ensure that the Ruby Ridge after action critique would not be 
available in the Weaver case, however, defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE withheld the 
Ruby Ridge after action critique from this compilation of documents, and failed 
otherwise to identify its existence. 

18. The Department of Justice eventually ordered, and the FBI eventually agreed, that all 
of the Ruby Ridge related Headquarters documents, including any disputed documents, 
should be produced to the prosecution team in Idaho. 

19. Defendant E. MICHAEL KAHOE supervised the production of these documents to 
the prosecution team. In order to ensure that the Ruby Ridge after action critique would 
not be available in the Weaver case, however, defendant J. MICHAEL KAHOE withheld 
the Ruby Ridge after action critique from the documents to be delivered to the U.S. 
Attorney's Office in Idaho or the local FBI case agents. 

20. To further ensure that the Ruby Ridge after action critique would not be available in 
the Weaver case, between on or about January 7, 1993 and early April, 1993, defendant 
E. MICHAEL KAHOE destroyed all of his copies of the Ruby Ridge after action critique. 

21. To further ensure that the Ruby Ridge after action critique would not be available in 
the Weaver case, between on or about January 7, 1993 and early April, 1993, defendant 
E. MICHAEL KAHOE ordered a subordinate FBI Headquarters official, whose identity 
its known to the United States, to destroy all copies of the Ruby Ridge after action 
critique and to make it appear as if the Ruby Ridge after action critique never existed. 

22. Between in or about January 7, 1993 and early April, 1993, in the District of 
Columbia and elsewhere, defendant 

E. MICHAEL KAHOE

did knowingly and corruptly persuade another person, and attempt to do so, with intent to 
cause and induce another person to destroy, mutilate and conceal the Ruby Ridge after 
action critique with the intent to impair its availability for use in an official proceeding, 
that is United States v. Randall C. Weaver and Kevin L. Harris, D. Idaho Crim. No. 92-
080-N-EJL. 

(Obstruction of Justice, in violation of Title 18, United States Code, Section 
1512(b)(2)(B)). 

Respectfully submitted,

___________________
MICHAEL R. STILES
Acting United States Attorney
for the District of Columbia
Pennsylvania Bar No. 22935

Eric W. Sitarchuk
Robert E. Goldman
Steven W. Pelak
Carol Fortine
Assistant United States Attorneys
555 4th Street, N.W.
Washington, D.C. 20001
(202) 514-8062


</PRE>
